name: US INTERNATIONAL TRADE COMMISSION (ITC)
description: The US International Trade Commission (ITC) is a government agency that ruled that Apple had infringed on two patents from Masimo, leading to an import ban on the Apple Watch Series 9 and Ultra 2 starting December 26th. [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: MASIMO
description: Masimo, a renowned medical device maker celebrated for its pulse oximetry technology, commonly known as SpO2 or blood oxygen saturation in the wearable tech industry, has been embroiled in a legal dispute with Apple since 2020. The company alleges that Apple has infringed upon its patents by utilizing Masimo's proprietary technology in the Apple Watch's blood oxygen sensor without obtaining the necessary licensing permissions. Masimo CEO, Joe Kiani, highlighted in an interview with The New York Times that Apple had not engaged in any licensing negotiations. The patents in question are hardware-related, and simply disabling the sensor might not suffice to circumvent the infringement. To date, Masimo has reportedly spent $60 million on litigation, demonstrating the company's commitment to protecting its intellectual property. The initial lawsuit was filed in the US District Court in the Central District of California, accusing Apple of stealing trade secrets and infringing on 10 of Masimo's patents. A subsequent case was brought to the International Trade Commission (ITC) in 2021, further escalating the legal battle between the two entities.

name: BEN LEVI
description: Ben Levi is a partner at Levi Snotherly & Schaumberg, a law firm with experience litigating ITC disputes. He comments on the situation, saying that Apple sees the writing on the wall and is preparing itself for the import ban. [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: LEVI SNOTHERLY & SCHAUMBERG
description: Levi Snotherly & Schaumberg is a law firm with experience litigating ITC disputes. Ben Levi, a partner at the firm, comments on the situation involving Apple and Masimo. [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: US CUSTOMS AGENCY
description: The US customs agency is a government organization responsible for regulating the import and export of goods. Apple plans to submit a workaround to this agency to reintroduce the Apple Watch to the market after facing a ban due to patent infringement claims by Masimo. [Source: The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: SPO2 SENSORS
description: SpO2 sensors are a technology used in the Apple Watch for wellness and sleep tracking. They take periodic readings of blood oxygen levels in the background or can be actively used for spot checks. However, Apple does not make wide use of these metrics for medical purposes, and the average Apple Watch user may forget about the blood oxygen features. [Source: The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: ITC
description: The ITC is a government agency that has ruled on the patent infringement case involving Apple and Masimo. The success of Apple's workaround to reintroduce the Apple Watch to the market depends on the specific patent, ITC ruling, and the significance of the changes Apple plans to make to the product. [Source: The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: JOE KIANI
description: Joe Kiani, the CEO of Masimo, a medical technology company, has accused Apple of patent infringement, as reported by The Verge on December 19, 2023. Masimo, under Kiani's leadership, has not only made allegations but has also taken legal action by filing a patent infringement lawsuit against Apple. In a New York Times interview, Kiani stated that Apple had not engaged in licensing negotiations with Masimo, suggesting a lack of effort from Apple to resolve the dispute amicably.

name: ALIVECOR
description: AliveCor is a company that has also accused Apple of patent infringement for using its technology in the Apple Watch's EKG features. The Patent Trial and Appeal Board ruled that AliveCor's EKG tech isn't actually patentable, but AliveCor would have to win its appeal to that ruling before any Apple Watches with EKG features would be pulled from the market for that reason. [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: BLOOD OXYGEN SENSOR
description: The blood oxygen sensor is a technology used in the Apple Watch that is at the center of the patent infringement dispute with Masimo. [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: EKG FEATURES
description: The EKG features are a technology used in the Apple Watch that is at the center of the patent infringement dispute with AliveCor. The Patent Trial and Appeal Board ruled that AliveCor's EKG tech isn't actually patentable, but AliveCor would have to win its appeal to that ruling before any Apple Watches with EKG features would be pulled from the market for that reason. [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: APPLE INC.
description: Apple Inc. is a technology company that produces the Apple Watch. The company claims that its product does not infringe on other people’s patented technology [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: PATENT INFRINGEMENT
description: Patent infringement is a legal issue where a product or technology is claimed to violate the exclusive rights granted to the holder of a patent. Apple Inc. is facing such claims regarding the import of certain Apple Watch models into the US [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: IMPORT BAN
description: An import ban is a legal action that prevents the importation of a product into a country. The US is considering an import ban on certain Apple Watch models due to patent infringement claims [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: THIRD-PARTY RESELLERS
description: Third-party resellers are businesses that sell products not made by themselves. In the context of the Apple Watch import ban, they can still sell their existing inventory of Series 9 and Ultra 2 models [The Verge, 2023-12-19]

name: ADOLIS GARCIA
description: Adolis Garcia is a slugger for the Rangers. His season was over before Game 4 of the 2023 World Series [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: COREY SEAGER
description: Corey Seager, a key player for the Rangers in the World Series 2023, has been instrumental in the team's performance. According to the Sporting News on October 31, 2023, Seager hit a significant 2-run home run, bolstering the Rangers' lead in the series. This was not his first impressive feat in the World Series, as he also hit his third home run of the series during Game 4, further solidifying his impact on the team's success.

name: MARCUS SIEEN
description: Marcus Sieen is a player for the Rangers. He drove in five of the Rangers' first 10 runs in Game 4, including a three-run blast that put Texas up by double digits [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: NATHAN EOVARDI
description: Nathan Eovaldi is a player for the Rangers. He will make his sixth start of the postseason in Game 5 [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: ZAC GALLEN
description: Zac Gallen is a player for the Diamondbacks. He will start for the Diamondbacks in Game 5 [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: MARCUS SEMIEN
description: Marcus Semien is a player for the Rangers who hit a 2-run triple, extending the team's lead in the World Series 2023. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: TRAVIS JANKOWSKI
description: Travis Jankowski is a player for the Rangers who singled up the middle, giving the team runners on first and second with two outs in the World Series 2023. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: CHRISTIAN WALKER
description: Christian Walker is a player for the Diamondbacks who had a chance to turn two but couldn't hold onto the ball, leading to the Rangers having the bases loaded with one out in the World Series 2023. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: ALEK THOMAS
description: Alek Thomas is a player for the Diamondbacks who is mentioned as coming up to bat after Gurriel hits a two-out single in the World Series 2023. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: ATL
description: ATL is a sports team that played against the Phillies in the Division Series of the World Series 2023. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: LAD
description: LAD is a sports team that played against the Diamondbacks in the Division Series of the World Series 2023. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: FS1
description: FS1 is a TV channel that broadcasted several games of the World Series 2023, including the Astros vs. Rangers and the Diamondbacks vs. Phillies. [Sporting News, 2023-10-31]

name: VAMPIRE FICTION
description: Vampire fiction has a long history in English literature, with authors reflecting the changing society through their stories about the undead. [Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: ROBERT SOUTHEY
description: Robert Southey introduced the concept of the coffin-sleeping undead to the British Isles at the turn of the 19th century. [Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: JOHN WILLIAM POLIDORI
description: John William Polidori is best known for his vampire book "The Vampyre" (1819), which was inspired by a story contest where Mary Shelley conceived the idea for Frankenstein. Polidori's novel was based on an idea from Lord Byron, who was too lazy to write the story himself. [Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: MARY SHELLEY
description: Mary Shelley is known for conceiving the idea for her novel "Frankenstein" during a spooky story contest at a Swiss chalet, which also led to the creation of John William Polidori's "The Vampyre." [Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: LORD BYRON
description: Lord Byron, a participant in the story contest, is depicted as a night-stalking, possibly vampiric figure. He passed the idea of an aristocratic Englishman secretly being an ancient, unkillable force of evil to John William Polidori, who developed it into "The Vampyre." [Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: BRAM STOKER
description: Bram Stoker, an Irish author, is best known for his iconic novel "Dracula," published in 1897, which has become a cornerstone in the vampire genre. The story revolves around a Transylvanian count who relocates to the U.K. to execute a centuries-old scheme of vampiric dominance and enslavement, serving as the inspiration for numerous vampire-related adaptations, parodies, and tropes. Stoker's fascination extended beyond literature to the esoteric, as he was involved in the occult studies of the Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn and had a keen interest in the history and practices of the Freemasons, adding layers of intrigue to his life and work. This information is sourced from Polygon on 2023-11-09, enriched with additional details about Stoker's life and interests.

name: ANNE RICE
description: Anne Rice, a renowned author, is celebrated for her groundbreaking Vampire Chronicles series (1976-2018), which introduced a new era in vampire literature by prominently featuring gay, campy, and unapologetically fabulous vampires, a move that was both innovative and influential in the genre. Despite speculation from Polygon in 2023 that her deep understanding of the allure of the undead might suggest she was a vampire herself, this is clearly a playful conjecture. Rice's relationship with Catholicism was complex and evolving; she initially turned away from the faith, later embraced it in the early 2000s to pen Christ-themed religious fiction, but ultimately rejected the Church due to its conservative social positions. This journey reflects the dynamic nature of her beliefs and the diverse themes she explored in her writing.

name: BYRON
description: Byron is a historical figure, a poet, who is described as mockingly contemptuous of others, yet desired by those around him. He is portrayed as a stand-in for a vampire in the context of John Polidori's almost unwilling attraction to him

name: JOHN POLIDORI
description: John Polidori was a writer and physician, best known for his work "The Vampyre," which was inspired by his relationship with Byron. He is characterized as having an almost unwilling attraction to Byron, marking him out as a classic human thrall of an undead overlord

name: DRACULA
description: "Dracula" is a novel by Bram Stoker published in 1897. It tells the story of a Transylvanian count who takes residence in the U.K. to launch a centuries-old plan of vampiric conquest and enslavement. The novel became the source of many vampire-related pastiches, spinoffs, and cliches

name: HERMETIC ORDER OF THE GOLDEN DAWN
description: The Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn is an organization that Bram Stoker took a keen interest in. It is associated with occult studies

name: FREEMASONS
description: Freemasons is an organization that Bram Stoker was interested in. It is associated with history and practices

name: STEPHEN KING
description: Stephen King, an American author with a striking resemblance to a vampire, has significantly modernized the vampire novel genre. He is famously known for his work "'Salem's Lot," published in 1975, which tells the story of a writer returning to his rural Maine hometown, only to find it under the control of the undead. This novel, among others, reflects King's post-Watergate suspicions of government corruption, suggesting that the rot had permeated every level of society. Despite surviving a car accident and maintaining a nocturnal schedule, King has remained in an ageless state throughout his career. He has also taken strong stances against corporate power and in favor of trans rights, advocating for the acceptance of all kinds, including the vampire kind. These views were highlighted in a Polygon article dated 2023-11-09. Stephen King's contributions to literature and his social commentary have made him a significant figure in the realm of technology and entertainment communities, where his works are often discussed and analyzed.

name: "'SALEM'S LOT"
description: "'Salem's Lot" is a novel by Stephen King published in 1975. It concerns a writer who returns to his childhood hometown in rural Maine, only to discover that the entire society is in thrall to the undead. The novel encapsulates post-Watergate suspicions that government corruption had infected all levels of the community

name: VAMPIRE NOVELS
description: Vampire novels have been used as allegories for the deepest fears of society, with the Victorian era using them to represent sexual urges, temptations, and repressed fears. Stephen King's novel "Salem's Lot" modernized the genre by encapsulating post-Watergate suspicions of government corruption [source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: THE VAMPIRE CHRONICLES
description: The Vampire Chronicles is a series of books by Anne Rice that prominently featured gay, campy, and unapologetically fabulous vampires, marking a significant shift in the genre [source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: LAURELL K. HAMILTON
description: Laurell K. Hamilton is an author best known for her Anita Blake: Vampire Hunter series, which she began writing in the early 2000s. Her work is characterized by a blend of sexiness and violence, akin to the aesthetic of a 1970s grindhouse flick. [Source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: ANITA BLAKE: VAMPIRE HUNTER SERIES
description: The Anita Blake: Vampire Hunter series is a collection of vampire-themed novels written by Laurell K. Hamilton, starting in 1993. The series is known for its merrily obscene aesthetic, where characters engage in violent and sexual activities, often in good fun. [Source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: TAIKA WAITITI
description: Taika Waititi is a filmmaker who co-created the vampire-themed comedy series "What We Do in the Shadows" along with Jemaine Clement. The series, which started as a movie in 2014, has become culturally pervasive and marks a significant shift in the vampire genre from horror to comedy. [Source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: WHAT WE DO IN THE SHADOWS
description: "What We Do in the Shadows" is a vampire-themed comedy series co-created by Taika Waititi and Jemaine Clement. The series, which began as a movie in 2014, has evolved the vampire genre into outright comedy, with only a faint twist of terror to remind audiences of its origins. [Source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: JEMAINE CLEMENT
description: Jemaine Clement is a filmmaker who co-created the vampire-themed comedy series "What We Do in the Shadows" with Taika Waititi. The series, which started as a movie in 2014, has become a significant piece of vampire-themed fiction in recent years. [Source: Polygon, 2023-11-09]

name: MARK SURMAN
description: Mark Surman is the president and executive director at the Mozilla Foundation, who commented on the OpenAI/Microsoft drama, highlighting the risks of centralizing AI technology under a few major players. [TechCrunch, 2023-11-21]

name: MOZILLA FOUNDATION
description: The Mozilla Foundation is an organization that published an open letter calling for more openness in AI development, signed by over 1,700 people including Meta’s chief AI scientist Yann LeCun. [TechCrunch, 2023-11-21]

name: YANN LECUN
description: Yann LeCun, a prominent computer scientist recognized for his contributions to machine learning and computer vision, serves as Meta's chief AI scientist. In 2023, LeCun co-authored an open letter advocating for increased transparency and openness in AI development, expressing his disagreement with the notion that proprietary AI systems are inherently safer than open-source alternatives. He has been vocal about his concerns regarding major AI companies' efforts to influence the industry by lobbying against open AI research and development, accusing them of attempting to secure regulatory capture to benefit their own interests. LeCun's stance highlights his commitment to fostering a more inclusive and collaborative AI ecosystem.

name: HUGGING FACE
description: Hugging Face, in collaboration with Meta, has launched a startup accelerator with the aim of accelerating the adoption of open source AI models. This initiative, announced on November 21, 2023, by TechCrunch, underscores Hugging Face's commitment to fostering innovation and accessibility in the field of artificial intelligence. By supporting startups through this accelerator, Hugging Face and Meta seek to drive the development and utilization of AI models that are freely available, promoting a more inclusive and dynamic technology ecosystem.

name: AI MODELS
description: AI models are advanced systems designed to perform tasks that typically require human intelligence, such as learning, reasoning, and perception. They are crucial in various industries for automation and decision-making processes [TechCrunch, 2023-11-21]

name: NORWAY'S DATA PROTECTION AUTHORITY
description: Norway’s data protection authority is a regulatory body that has issued a local ban on Meta tracking and profiling users without consent, using powers under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) to protect citizens’ data. The authority has asked the European Union regulator to make the emergency sanction permanent and apply it across the EU single market, not just locally. The Datatilsynet issued the ban in July, and Meta has continued to ignore the order, leading to a court injunction against the order which was rejected by an Oslo court. The authority has the option to refer ongoing concerns to the EDPB, which it has now done. [Source: TechCrunch, 2023-09-28]

name: EUROPEAN UNION REGULATOR
description: The European Union regulator is responsible for making binding decisions on data protection issues across the EU single market. The Norwegian data protection authority has asked the EU regulator to take a binding decision on whether the emergency sanction on Meta should be made permanent and applied across the EU single market. [Source: TechCrunch, 2023-09-28]

name: EUROPEAN DATA PROTECTION BOARD (EDPB)
description: The European Data Protection Board (EDPB) is a regulatory body that could lead to a blanket ban on Meta running tracking ads without consent across the EU single market if it agrees the action is merited. The EDPB confirmed receipt of the Norwegian authority’s request and will assess the completeness of the file. [Source: TechCrunch, 2023-09-28]

name: EDPB
description: EDPB, the European Data Protection Board, is the body to which the Norwegian DPA referred the case regarding Meta's unlawful ads. The referral may concentrate minds at Meta on the need to make good on its pledge to ask users' permission for tracking and profiling sooner rather than later. [Source: TechCrunch, 2023-09-28]

name: NORWEGIAN DPA
description: The Norwegian DPA, or Norwegian data protection authority, decided to take emergency action against Meta for continuing to run unlawful ads in the EU/EEA. The DPA referred the case to the EDPB, pointing out that millions of EU people's rights are being infringed. [Source: TechCrunch, 2023-09-28]

name: MATT POLLARD
description: Matt Pollard is a spokesperson for Meta. He sought to deflect attention off of the current lack of compliance with EU data protection laws, stating that Meta has already committed to moving to the legal basis of consent for advertising in the EU/EEA. Pollard declined to specify a timeframe for the transition. [Source: TechCrunch, 2023-09-28]

name: IRELAND'S DPC
description: Ireland's Data Protection Commission (DPC) is the regulatory body responsible for enforcing privacy rights in the EU's single market. People are directed to wait on the DPC to enforce their privacy rights against Meta.[]

name: EU'S SINGLE MARKET
description: The EU's single market is a region where people are once again being directed to wait on Ireland's DPC to enforce their privacy rights.[]

name: NORWAY
description: Norway is seeking to extend the ban on Meta's consentless tracking ads across the EU.[]

name: THE BOARD
description: The Board is a regulatory body that can step in if the Irish authority is too slow to rectify Meta's lack of consent, and finish the job for it.[]

name: LEGAL SPORTS BETTING
description: Legal sports betting is now available in over 30 states, making it easier to bet on basketball at the best NBA betting sites [Source: Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA BETTING
description: NBA betting, a form of gambling centered around the National Basketball Association (NBA) games, involves placing wagers on a variety of outcomes and events. This includes bets on point spreads, moneylines, over/under bets, props, and futures markets. Futures betting, a common aspect of NBA betting, allows individuals to predict various long-term outcomes, such as championship winners or individual player awards, with odds typically favoring the bettor the further away the event is. These bets can be placed throughout the year, even before the season starts and during the regular season, through licensed sportsbooks. The activity of betting on NBA games provides an engaging way for fans to participate in the excitement of the sport and potentially profit from their predictions. [Source: Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: BOSTON CELTICS
description: The Boston Celtics are a professional basketball team in the NBA, whose betting odds can vary among different sportsbooks. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: DEPOSITS AND PAYOUTS
description: Deposits and payouts refer to the financial transactions involved in sports betting, where bettors deposit money into their sportsbook accounts and withdraw winnings. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: USER EXPERIENCE
description: User experience encompasses the ease of navigation, efficiency of customer support, and overall smoothness of using a sportsbook's website or app for NBA betting. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: SAFETY AND SECURITY
description: Safety and security refer to the measures taken by sportsbooks to protect users' personal information and ensure a secure betting environment. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: ONLINE SPORTS BETTING APPS
description: Online sports betting apps, such as DraftKings, FanDuel, and BetMGM, have increased the popularity of in-game betting, allowing bettors to place bets on a game while it's unfolding. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA ODDS PAGE
description: The NBA odds page is a resource that can be used to find the best lines for prospective bets. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NCAA BASKETBALL
description: NCAA basketball is a college basketball league, with its own betting sites. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: 2023-24 NBA SEASON
description: The 2023-24 NBA season includes the regular season, in-season tournament, All-Star Weekend, regular season end, play-in tournament, playoffs, and NBA Finals. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA POINT SPREADS
description: NBA point spreads are a type of bet where the margin of victory or loss is the focus. For example, if the New York Knicks are -7.5 favorites over the Miami Heat, the Knicks need to win by 8 points for a spread bet to win. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA MONEYLINES
description: NBA moneylines are the simplest form of betting, where the bettor picks the winner of the game. Favorites have negative odds, and underdogs have positive odds. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA OVER/UNDER BETS
description: NBA over/under bets, also known as totals, focus on the combined point total of the two teams playing in a game, regardless of the winner. For example, in a Knicks vs. Heat game, the over/under could be set at 211.5 points. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA PROPS AND FUTURES
description: NBA props and futures are types of bets that focus on specific player or team performances and events that will happen in the future. Player props could include points scored or rebounds, while team props can range from the first bucket to the total points scored in a quarter. Futures bets are on events that will happen in the future, such as the winner of the NBA Finals. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: NBA BETTING LEGALITY
description: The legality of NBA betting in the U.S. has evolved considerably. While NBA betting is permitted, the specific regulations vary by state. [Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: BETTING-FRIENDLY STATES
description: Over 30 states in the US have embraced sports betting, including wagers on the NBA, since the 2018 Supreme Court decision. For those residing or visiting these states, the experience promises fairness and security. State-regulated online betting platforms are in place, ensuring that bettors receive fair odds and adhere to strict standards for a safe and transparent betting environment. [Source: Sporting News, 2023-10-02]

name: COHEN
description: Cohen, the defense attorney representing Sam Bankman-Fried in his legal trial, has been characterized by a lack of organization and preparedness in his cross-examination efforts. Throughout the proceedings, Cohen's performance has largely failed to engage the jury, with reports indicating that his presentation was so monotonous that it caused at least two jurors to fall asleep. His approach to questioning has been described as disjointed, with the lawyer often starting on one topic only to suddenly switch to another without clear transition or purpose. Additionally, Cohen has shown a puzzling lack of recall regarding the testimony provided by Ellison, a key witness in the case, attempting to reference statements that she never actually made. This has resulted in Cohen being outmaneuvered by Ellison during her testimony, further highlighting the defense lawyer's apparent struggles with preparation and focus.

name: ELLISON
description: Ellison is an individual who reacted differently to stress than Sam Bankman-Fried. She avoided media while Bankman-Fried sought it out. She had conversations with investors as part of their due diligence. The defense suggested that the government had coerced her testimony, by suggesting that she had pleaded guilty to a charge of defrauding investors that she couldn’t have been involved in. During the cross-examination, she appeared to even be toying with Cohen [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: ELISON
description: Elison is a witness in the legal case against Sam Bankman-Fried. She is a former employee of Alameda Research, a trading firm associated with FTX. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: LUNA
description: Luna is a cryptocurrency token that was associated with Terra, another cryptocurrency. Elison testified about Luna during the legal proceedings. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: TERRA
description: Terra is a cryptocurrency token that was paired with Luna as an algorithmic stablecoin. Cohen asked Elison about the relationship between Terra and Luna, but she pointed out that she had only testified about Luna. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: CARLTON ELLISON
description: Carlton Ellison is an individual who confessed to stealing billions of FTX customers' money at the direction of Sam Bankman-Fried. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: CHRISTIAN DRAPPI
description: Christian Drappi is a former Alameda software engineer who testified about the theft of FTX customer funds and the subsequent meeting where Carlton Ellison confessed. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: BARBARA FRIED
description: Barbara Fried is Sam Bankman-Fried's mother who looked unhappy during the trial, possibly due to the unfolding events. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: JOSEPH BANKMAN
description: Joseph Bankman is Sam Bankman-Fried's father and a senior advisor to FTX's philanthropic arm, who was not present during the recording of the meeting. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: ZAC PRINCE
description: Zac Prince is the founder and former CEO of crypto lender BlockFi, who blamed FTX's bankruptcy for BlockFi's subsequent bankruptcy. [The Verge, 2023-10-12]

name: MAILGAN
description: Maignan is a person associated with the football match between Newcastle and Milan. He was only beaten once by Newcastle's shots. [The Independent - Sports, 2023-12-13]

name: POPE
description: Pope is a person associated with Newcastle. His injury and loss may have proved pivotal in the match against Milan. [The Independent - Sports, 2023-12-13]

name: DUBRAVKA
description: Dubravka is a person associated with Newcastle. He conceded twice in the match against Milan. [The Independent - Sports, 2023-12-13]

name: KIERAN TRIPPIER
description: Kieran Trippier is a person associated with Newcastle. He was taken off in the match against Milan because he seemed exhausted. [The Independent - Sports, 2023-12-13]

name: ANTHONY GORDON
description: Anthony Gordon is a person associated with Newcastle. He was taken off in the match against Milan because he seemed exhausted. [The Independent - Sports, 2023-12-13]

name: HIPCAGNOSIS SONGS CAPITAL (HSC)
description: Hipgnosis Songs Capital (HSC) is a company backed by Blackstone, involved in a potential transaction to acquire 29 music catalogs from Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF) for USD $440 million [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: HIPCAGNOSIS SONGS FUND (HSF)
description: Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF) is a publicly-traded fund that has announced its intention to explore the sale of 29 music catalogs to Hipgnosis Songs Capital (HSC) for USD $440 million, with the aim of potentially increasing its share price [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: MERCK MERCURIAIDIS
description: Merck Mercuriadis is the person who runs and is part-owner of Hipgnosis Song Management (HSM), the investment advisor for both Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF) and Hipgnosis Songs Capital (HSC) [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: HIPGNOSIS SONG MANAGEMENT (HSM)
description: Hipgnosis Song Management (HSM) is the investment advisor for Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF) and Hipgnosis Songs Capital (HSC), run and part-owned by Merck Mercuriadis [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: ANDREW SUTCH
description: Andrew Sutch, a 73-year-old individual, has been serving as the Chair of the board for Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF) since 2018. As of September 28, 2023, it was announced by Music Business Worldwide that Sutch is stepping down from his position as HSF board Chair and as a director of the company. In relation to this, a 'continuation vote' is anticipated to occur on October 26, 2023, which may have implications for the future direction of Hipgnosis Songs Fund.

name: ANDREW WILKINSON
description: Andrew Wilkinson, 72, has informed the Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF) board of his intention to retire as a board director, which will reduce the company’s board to five directors [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: HSF
description: HSF, also known as Hipgnosis Songs Fund, is a publicly traded company that has been listed since 2018, primarily engaged in the management and ownership of music copyrights. As of September 28, 2023, HSF is in the process of selling 29 of its music catalogs. Should a 'superior proposal' emerge during the 'go-shop' period, this could potentially lead to the adjournment of the HSF Annual General Meeting (AGM) and push the 2023 'continuation vote' into November, as reported by Music Business Worldwide.

name: HSM
description: Hipgnosis Songs Management (HSM), acting as the investment advisor for Hipgnosis Songs Fund (HSF), holds a significant 'matching right' on behalf of Hipgnosis Songs Collection (HSC). This right enables HSC to counteract a superior offer from a competitor for the acquisition of 29 music catalogs originally from HSF, potentially compelling HSF to sell these assets to HSC rather than to the rival bidder. HSM's role is pivotal in managing HSF's extensive music copyright portfolio, ensuring strategic and profitable decisions are made concerning its assets. [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: IAA
description: IAA, or Investment Advisory Agreement, is a contract between HSF and HSM that outlines the terms of HSM's role as HSF's investment advisor. [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: 2026 CONTINUATION VOTE
description: 2026 Continuation Vote is a scheduled event where HSF shareholders will decide whether to continue the company's operations. [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: 2023 CONTINUATION VOTE
description: 2023 Continuation Vote is an event where HSF shareholders will decide whether to continue the company's operations. [Music Business Worldwide, 2023-09-28]

name: HSC
description: Hipgnosis Songs Capital (HSC) is currently engaged in a significant bidding process for the acquisition of 29 music catalogs from HSF. HSC has put forth a substantial offer of $440 million, demonstrating their serious interest in expanding their music portfolio. Moreover, HSC holds a 'matching right', which allows them to counter any higher bids from competitors, ensuring they have the opportunity to secure the deal at the same price. This strategic move by Hipgnosis Songs Capital highlights their commitment to growing their presence in the music industry, as reported by Music Business Worldwide on September 28, 2023.

name: HIV
description: HIV, or Human Immunodeficiency Virus, is a virus that primarily targets the immune system, leading to AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome) if not treated. While it can affect individuals of all ages, it has become a manageable, chronic disease, particularly among the elderly, with about a quarter of people with HIV worldwide, and approximately half of adults with HIV in Western and Central Europe and North America, being at least 50 years old. The virus can be suppressed with cART (combination antiretroviral therapy), which helps in managing the condition effectively, although it cannot be completely eradicated from the body. The overarching goal from 2015 to 2030 is to prevent new HIV infections and reduce AIDS-related deaths, as highlighted in the Live Science articles dated 2023-11-30 and 2023-12-01.

name: 95-95-95 TARGET
description: The "95-95-95" target is a major goal set for 2025 to achieve 95% of people with HIV knowing their status, 95% of those diagnosed taking HIV drugs, and 95% of those treated being virally suppressed [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-12-01]

name: ART (ANTIRETROVIRAL THERAPY)
description: ART, or antiretroviral therapy, is a treatment for HIV that was taken by only 76% of the total 39 million people with HIV worldwide in 2022 [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-12-01]

name: UNAIDS
description: UNAIDS, a leading organization in the global fight against HIV and AIDS, has established ambitious targets for HIV treatment by 2025, known as the 95-95-95 goals. These objectives aim to ensure that 95% of individuals living with HIV are aware of their status, 95% of those diagnosed receive sustained antiretroviral therapy (ART), and 95% of those on ART achieve viral suppression. As of 2022, UNAIDS reported that 71% of people with HIV had reached viral suppression, indicating significant progress toward the 2025 targets. However, the organization also highlighted challenges in pediatric HIV treatment, noting that many drugs for children are unpalatable, difficult to administer, or require multiple daily doses, which can hinder adherence and effectiveness. Despite these hurdles, UNAIDS continues to monitor and report on HIV and AIDS statistics, driving efforts to improve treatment outcomes and quality of life for those affected by the disease.

name: ISRAEL MONEY LAUNDERING AND TERROR FINANCING PROHIBITION AUTHORITY (IMPA)
description: IMPA is an intelligence body that conducts international economic investigations and fights terror financing. It received secret intelligence information from two European countries about a large organization raising funds for Hamas through social networks and fintech platforms. The information was acted upon swiftly, leading to the blocking of the organization's money pipeline and the freezing of its financial activities. This action was taken without court orders or delay, resulting in the real-time deterrence of millions of dollars being transferred to Hamas's military arm. IMPA's director general, Ilit Ostrovitch-Levi, highlights the importance of worldwide cooperation in thwarting the transfer of funds earmarked for terrorism. Since May 2022, IMPA has been headed by Ostrovitch-Levi, and during the war, it has focused on identifying and blocking terror money pipelines. IMPA issued a call to all global regulated entities for increased vigilance towards terrorism financing campaigns in response to the ongoing war and state of emergency. [Globes English | Israel Business Arena, 2023-11-19])("entity"

Goods worth hundreds of thousands of shekels were seized at Ashdod Port, destined for Hamas merchants in Nablus and other cities, with the proceeds intended to finance Hamas operations.

name: TURKEY
description: The given descriptions are contradictory as one refers to the geopolitical entity, Turkey, and the other to the bird commonly associated with Thanksgiving in America. In the context of the geopolitical entity, Turkey is a country that plays a role in the financial transactions of Gazan merchants, where money changers receive funds from Hamas abroad and use them to pay Turkish companies for goods imported by these merchants. On the other hand, in the context of the bird, Turkey is a traditional food served during the American Thanksgiving holiday, with an estimated 46 million turkeys slaughtered annually for the occasion. A unique tradition involves the pardoning of two turkeys each year by the President of the United States, as reported by The Independent - Life and Style on November 11, 2023. However, it's important to note that "Turkey" as a geopolitical entity and "Turkey" as a bird are not related and should not be confused.

They have the ability to build the intelligence scenario, synchronize all the sources of information received, and delineate the money trail from abroad to Hamas. They are interested not only in who is running the campaign, the association or entity, but where the money is coming from, and where it’s going. They need to stop all of the elements in this network.

name: ANDREA GACKI
description: Andrea Gacki is the Director of the US Treasury Department's Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) who contacted IMPA's Ostrovitch-Levi three days after the start of the war to request a meeting. She put herself and the entity she heads, one of the most powerful financial intelligence agencies in the world, at their disposal. She said, 'Whatever you want or need, just say the word'. Gacki has kept her promise and since that day, IMPA has received an unprecedented flow of financial intelligence from the US, unlike anything seen before. They’ve given valuable information that has been passed on to the security agencies, about organizations they didn’t necessarily know about.

name: MXENES
description:
MXenes, also known as MBenes, are a class of 2-D, nano-scale materials characterized by their high diversity and tunability, which stem from alternating layers of transition metal (M) and another element such as carbon or nitrogen (X) atoms. These materials can be customized by modifying the mix of M and X atoms and further treated with various chemicals to alter their behavior, making them versatile for different applications. Notably, MXenes have been tailored for use in batteries and energy storage devices, showcasing their potential in the technology sector.

One of the most promising applications of MXenes is in carbon capture, where their vast surface area—comparable to that of a football field per gram—enables them to efficiently absorb carbon dioxide from the air, potentially contributing to climate change mitigation. However, MXenes can degrade into oxides in the presence of oxygen, which reduces their reactivity. Scientists are actively researching ways to enhance their structure to overcome this limitation and improve their durability for CO2 capture and release cycles.

Despite their mechanical ruggedness and strength comparable to steel, the production of MXenes is currently challenging due to the difficulty in scaling up their manufacturing. The process is energy-intensive, leading to a significant carbon footprint and high production costs. As of 2023, the full extent of their durability for carbon capture applications has not been thoroughly tested, indicating a need for further research to fully realize their potential in environmental and technological contexts.

This gas is released in large quantities due to human activities. Interestingly, certain MXenes have the capability to capture CO2, offering a potential solution to mitigate its climate-warming effects. [Source: Science News For Students, 2023-12-15]

They could have unique mechanical and electrical properties that might help them last through many cycles of CO2 capture and release. [Source: Science News For Students, 2023-12-15]

name: PHAGE THERAPY
description: Phage therapy is a treatment method that uses bacteriophages, viruses that infect bacteria, to combat bacterial infections. Unlike antibiotics, bacteria are unlikely to gain widespread resistance to phage therapy because phages can have much narrower targets than even narrow-spectrum antibiotics. This therapy has been tested through a regulatory framework known as "compassionate use" and has shown success in treating infections in patients with no other treatment options [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: ANTIBIOTICS
description: Antibiotics, a class of drugs used to treat bacterial infections, play a crucial role in modern medicine. However, their misuse and overuse, particularly in the case of broad-spectrum antibiotics that are effective against a wide range of bacteria, have significantly accelerated the evolution of bacterial resistance. This phenomenon has given rise to "superbugs," bacteria that are resistant to multiple antibiotics, posing a serious threat to public health. The information is sourced from Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, dated 2023-10-01, which highlights the critical need for responsible antibiotic use to prevent the further development of these resistant strains.

name: E. COLI
description: E. coli is a type of bacteria that can cause various infections in humans. A phage called U136B can infiltrate E. coli by using an efflux pump, a protein E. coli normally uses to pump antibiotics out of the cell. If E. coli tries to change this pump to escape the phage, it reduces the bacterium's ability to pump out antibiotics [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: PAUL TURNER
description: Paul Turner is a scientist and the director of the Center for Phage Biology and Therapy at Yale University. He has stated that if phage therapy were used at a global scale, it would not lead to the same problem of widespread resistance as antibiotic use has. Turner and other experts have concluded that phage therapy can be an effective treatment for bacterial infections [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: CENTER FOR PHAGE BIOLOGY AND THERAPY
description: The Center for Phage Biology and Therapy at Yale University is a research institute that focuses on the study of bacteriophages and their potential use in treating bacterial infections. Paul Turner is the director of this center [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: CRISPR-CAS SYSTEM
description: The CRISPR-Cas system is a genetic engineering tool that can be used to snip DNA at precise locations. A Cas enzyme is preparing to cut through a target DNA strand and is being told where to cut [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: PHAGES
description: Phages, the entities in question, are viruses with a unique ability to infect and kill bacteria, making them a promising avenue for potential therapy in treating bacterial infections within clinical settings (Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01). The mechanism by which phages destroy bacteria involves targeting essential cell-wall components that are difficult for bacteria to alter, thus minimizing the likelihood of promoting resistance. To enhance their effectiveness and ensure they target the correct bacteria, CRISPR machinery can be loaded into a phage, enabling it to precisely infect the intended bacterial strain. This strategic approach to utilizing phages could revolutionize the fight against antibiotic-resistant bacteria, offering a more targeted and less resistance-prone alternative to traditional antibiotics.

name: CRISPR-CAS
description: CRISPR-Cas is an immune system found in many bacteria that can be used as a powerful gene-editing tool. It includes molecular scissors, known as Cas proteins, and a memory bank of DNA snippets that a bacterium has collected from phages that once infected it. The system can guide its lethal scissors to a precise point in an invading phage's DNA and snip it [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: CHASE BEISEL
description: Chase Beisel is a scientist who co-founded and is a scientific adviser to Locus Biosciences, a biotech company testing a CRISPR-enhanced phage therapy in a midstage, roughly 800-person trial. He is also involved in exploring the use of CRISPR-Cas to shred bacterial cells' DNA [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: LOCUS BIOSCIENCES
description: Locus Biosciences is a biotech company that is currently testing a CRISPR-enhanced phage therapy in a midstage, roughly 800-person trial. The company is exploring the use of phages coupled with CRISPR-Cas to destroy essential bacterial genes [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: BACTERIA
description: Bacteria are living organisms that can be infected by phages. They have an immune system called CRISPR-Cas that can guide its lethal scissors to a precise point in an invading phage's DNA and snip it. Bacteria can also have helpful bacteria in the body that should not be hurt by phage therapies [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: LYSINS
description: Lysins are enzymes produced by phages that can quickly kill bacteria upon contact. They are specific, targeting certain types of bacteria while sparing others. Lysins can be modified in the lab to change their targets, increase potency, and improve durability in the body. [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: SUPERBUGS
description: Superbugs are bacteria that have developed resistance to multiple antibiotics. They pose a growing threat to human health as traditional antibiotics become less effective. [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: DR. SHRUTI GOHIL
description: Dr. Shruti Gohil is a lead investigator of four INSPIRE-ASP Trials, federally funded research aimed at improving hospitals' antibiotic use. She advocates for antibiotic stewardship to prevent the rise of superbugs. [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: INSPIRE-ASP TRIALS
description: INSPIRE-ASP Trials are federally funded research projects aimed at improving hospitals' antibiotic use. They involve auditing doctors' prescriptions and promoting the use of narrower-spectrum drugs. [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-10-01]

name: EBT-101
description: EBT-101 is a CRISPR-based treatment targeting multiple sites in the genome to suppress HIV in infected primates and now being tested in humans for safety and efficacy in an early-stage clinical trial [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-11-30]

name: CRISPR
description: CRISPR is a gene editing technology that can alter DNA at targeted sites, but also has potential for off-target effects which can lead to complications [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-11-30]

name: CART
description: cART (combination antiretroviral therapy) is a treatment that suppresses HIV replication in patients, keeping the virus in check but not curing it [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-11-30]

name: HERRERA-CARRILLO
description: Herrera-Carrillo is an expert who emphasized the need for caution in the EBT-101 clinical trial, acknowledging the positive safety profile but highlighting the substantial work still required to determine the treatment's efficacy [Live Science: The Most Interesting Articles, 2023-11-30]

name: NIKE
description:
Nike, a global sportswear multinational corporation, reported its fiscal first quarter results, showcasing a revenue of $12.94 billion, a 2% increase from the previous year's $12.69 billion, albeit below Wall Street's expectations. The company's net income for the quarter ending August 31 stood at $1.45 billion, or 94 cents per share, compared to $1.47 billion, or 93 cents per share, in the year-ago period. Despite the slight dip in gross margin to 44.2%, down about 0.1 percentage points, it surpassed analysts' expectations of 43.7%, contributing to a post-market stock surge. Nike maintained its full-year guidance, projecting revenue growth in the mid-single digits and a gross margin expansion of 1.4 to 1.6 percentage points.

In the first quarter, Nike's footwear sales experienced a 4% growth to $8.4 billion, accounting for approximately 68% of total sales, while apparel sales saw a 1% decline, totaling $3.4 billion. The company is focusing on direct sales and digital channels for future growth, as inventories fell 10% to $8.7 billion, driven by a decrease in units but offset by product mix and higher manufacturing and production costs.

Nike has restored its relationship with Macy's and DSW, and is in the process of resetting its business with Footlocker, indicating a strategic realignment in its distribution channels. The company remains optimistic about China, where sales grew by 5% to $1.7 billion, albeit below the $1.8 billion analysts had anticipated, reflecting a slowed economic recovery in the region. Despite these challenges, Nike's member engagement within its direct business has seen double-digit growth, and its stores have performed strongly in the quarter, highlighting the company's resilience and adaptability in the face of market fluctuations.

name: WALL STREET
description: Wall Street is a financial market where analysts had set expectations for Nike's fiscal first quarter results, expecting revenue of $12.98 billion and earnings per share of 75 cents. Nike's actual results fell short of these revenue expectations but beat on earnings and gross margin estimates. [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

name: LSEG
description: LSEG, formerly known as Refinitiv, is a company that conducted a survey of analysts to set expectations for Nike's fiscal first quarter results. [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

name: MATTHEW FRIEND
description: Matthew Friend is Nike's finance chief who commented on the company's operating environment, including foreign currency exchange rates, consumer demand over the holiday season, and its second half wholesale order book. He also mentioned that Nike is cautiously planning for modest markdown improvements for the balance of the year, given the promotional environment. [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

description: Dick's Sporting Goods is a sportswear retailer that Nike has identified as one of its key partners [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

description: Donahoe is a representative of Nike who made it clear to analysts that Nike is ready to meet customers in all channels, including through wholesalers and directly [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

description: Friend is a representative of Nike who highlighted the strong performance of Nike's stores and the decrease in inventories, and also mentioned the restoration of relationships with Macy's and DSW and the process of resetting the business with Footlocker [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

name: CONSUMERS
description: Consumers have been reducing their spending on apparel and footwear due to high inflation rates. A survey by Jefferies found that 54% of respondents plan to spend less on apparel and accessories, and 46% plan to spend less on footwear [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

description: The resumption of student loan payments is expected to further impact consumer spending on apparel and footwear, potentially leading to a greater hit for Nike [Cnbc | World Business News Leader, 2023-09-28]

name: BRIDE
description: The bride, Calla, made a heartfelt decision to have her mother accompany her down the aisle at her wedding, a choice that was driven by her desire to honor the memory of her late father. Calla's decision, as reported by The Independent - Life and Style on 2023-11-27, highlights the importance of personal connection and the role of family dynamics in shaping wedding ceremonies.

The incident drew mixed reactions from Reddit users, some of whom criticized Calla for her choice, while others supported her right to decide who would play a pivotal role in her special day. Despite the emotional fallout, the stepfather's presence in Calla's life underscores the complex dynamics that can exist within blended families, particularly around significant life events.

name: EU COMMISSION
description:
The EU Commission, a significant governmental body, actively engages in shaping the technological landscape within the European Union. In a recent development, the Commission confirmed its pivotal role in the political deal over the EU AI Act, which empowers it to adapt the pan-EU AI rulebook to maintain alignment with advancements in the AI field. This flexibility is crucial for addressing the dynamic nature of AI technologies. The Commission announced the establishment of a new expert oversight body, the AI Office, which will oversee the implementation of AI regulations and ensure they remain effective and relevant.

Additionally, the EU Commission addressed the FLOPs threshold for high-risk GPAIs, clarifying that the initial threshold is subject to updates through implementing or delegating acts, reflecting the Commission's commitment to a flexible and responsive regulatory framework.

However, the EU Commission has also been embroiled in controversy regarding its involvement in the CSAM-scanning proposal. Accusations of employing "spin-doctor" tactics to discredit an investigative report by BalkanInsight have been leveled against the Commission. Fotiadis warned that such actions could potentially lead to attacks on journalists, highlighting the importance of maintaining transparency and integrity in the Commission's dealings with the media and public scrutiny. These events underscore the dual role of the EU Commission in both advancing technology policy and managing its public image amidst sensitive issues.

name: COMMISSION
description: The Commission is the body that has set up the AI Office and has developed the AI Act, which includes rules for GPAIs. The Commission has suggested that the 25 FLOPs threshold was chosen to capture current gen frontier models. [TechCrunch, 2023-12-11]

name: GPAIS
description: GPAIS, also known as General Purpose AI Systems or General Purpose Artificial Intelligences, are versatile AI systems capable of handling a broad spectrum of tasks and applications. According to the TechCrunch report dated 2023-12-11, these systems have been categorized under a high-risk tier by the AI Act, which will impose ex ante-style regulatory requirements on them. This means that GPAIS will be obligated to proactively assess and mitigate systemic risks associated with their operations. In the interim, while awaiting the full implementation of these regulations, GPAIS are expected to adhere to codes of practice as outlined by the EU AI Act, ensuring compliance and responsible AI usage.

name: GPAI
description: GPAI, or General Purpose Artificial Intelligence, refers to AI systems that can perform a wide range of tasks and will face transparency requirements, including watermarking on generative AI outputs, under the EU's risk-based framework. The framework was originally presented by the Commission in April 2021 and has been updated to include GPAIs. [TechCrunch, 2023-12-11]

name: EU COPYRIGHT DIRECTIVE
description: The EU Copyright Directive is a set of rules that governs copyright in the European Union and includes an opt-out from text and data mining for GPAIs. The directive will still apply to open source GPAIs. [TechCrunch, 2023-12-11]

name: SCIENTIFIC ADVISORY PANEL
description: The Scientific Advisory Panel is a new body that will be established under the EU's risk-based framework to aid the AI Office in understanding the capabilities of advanced AI models and identifying new risks that may arise. [TechCrunch, 2023-12-11]

name: ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE OFFICE
description: The Artificial Intelligence Office is an entity that will be aided by a scientific panel to understand new risks associated with AI models [TechCrunch, 2023-12-11]

name: SCIENTIFIC PANEL
description: A scientific panel will be set up to help the Artificial Intelligence Office identify new risks that AI models might pose [TechCrunch, 2023-12-11]

name: YLVAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
description: Ylva Johansson is the European Union's home affairs commissioner who spearheaded a controversial child sexual abuse material (CSAM)-scanning proposal and is involved in an investigation regarding the use of microtargeted political ads

name: DANNY MEKIC

name: DE VOLKSKRANT

name: CSAM-SCANNING PROPOSAL
description: The CSAM-scanning proposal, a policy topic of significant interest and controversy, is spearheaded by Ylva Johansson. This proposal advocates for the implementation of technology to scan digital platforms for child sexual abuse material (CSAM), aiming to curb the online distribution of such content. However, the initiative has encountered opposition from certain EU countries, highlighting the complex legal and ethical landscape surrounding digital surveillance and privacy. The scrutiny and debate surrounding the CSAM-scanning proposal intensified following a report by investigative journalists published by BalkanInsight last month. The report shed light on the close contacts between Johansson's department and companies that sell CSAM-scanning and other child safety tools, raising questions about the potential influence of commercial interests on policy-making. As of October 25, 2023, the proposal remains a subject of public and political debate, with stakeholders discussing the balance between child protection and privacy rights.

name: JOHANSSON
description: Johansson, a prominent political figure, has proposed a regulation for scanning private messages in a bid to combat Child Sexual Abuse Material (CSAM), as highlighted in a TechCrunch article dated 2023-10-25. She emphasizes that this measure is not an act of mass surveillance but a limited intervention aimed at protecting children. Johansson's department has reportedly maintained close contacts with companies that specialize in selling CSAM-scanning and other child safety tools, showcasing a proactive stance in leveraging technology for child protection. Amidst these efforts, she faced criticism from an investigative report by BalkanInsight, which she dismissed as a series of insinuations seeking attention. Johansson staunchly defended her actions against allegations of financial influence, asserting her commitment to the cause of child safety.

name: BALKANINSIGHT
description: BalkanInsight is a media outlet that published an investigative report last month looking at close contacts between Johansson’s department and companies selling CSAM-scanning and other child safety tools. [TechCrunch, 2023-10-25]

name: APOSTOLIS FOTIAIDIS
description: Apostolis Fotiadis is a journalist involved in the investigation and reporting on the CSAM-scanning proposal. He was invited by the LIBE committee to participate in the exchange of views and defended the reporting from direct public attacks by Johansson. He expressed surprise at the Commission’s reaction to the scrutiny and warned against using “spin-doctor” tactics to discredit the article. [TechCrunch, 2023-10-25]

name: LIBE COMMITTEE
description: The LIBE committee is a political committee that invited Apostolis Fotiadis to participate in the exchange of views on the CSAM-scanning proposal. The committee asked Fotiadis about the accusation that the journalists had been spreading disinformation and whether Johansson and the Commission’s response amounted to a restriction on media freedom. [TechCrunch, 2023-10-25]

name: EDPS
description: The EDPS (European Data Protection Supervisor) is an organization that has warned about the potential impact on freedom and democracy if the EU proceeds with non-targeted scanning of private messages, as stated in [TechCrunch, 2023-10-25]

name: CSAM
description: CSAM (Child Sexual Abuse Material) is the content that Johansson's proposal aims to detect and prevent through scanning of private messages, as detailed in [TechCrunch, 2023-10-25]

name: MEPS
description: On October 25, 2023, as reported by TechCrunch, Members of the European Parliament (MEPs) are actively engaged in a dual-front discussion concerning the digital privacy landscape in the European Union. The first issue involves a proposed regulation that would mandate the scanning of private messages, a measure that has sparked significant debate among the MEPs. Simultaneously, they are also questioning the EU Commissioner regarding the controversial topic of CSAM (Child Sexual Abuse Material) microtargeting, a practice that raises concerns about privacy and the effectiveness of combating online abuse. The MEPs' involvement in these discussions highlights their role in shaping the future of digital privacy laws and their commitment to addressing the complex challenges of online safety and privacy in the EU.

name: EU COMMISSIONER
description: The EU Commissioner is a person who is sidestepping MEPs' questions about CSAM microtargeting, relying on the existence of a wider EU legal framework to protect Europeans' fundamental rights and invoking respect for the rule of law to address the risk of content-scanning mission creep [Source: TechCrunch, Time: 2023-10-25]

name: CSAM MICROTARGETING
description: CSAM microtargeting is a technology or issue related to child sexual abuse online that is being questioned by MEPs and sidestepped by the EU Commissioner [Source: TechCrunch, Time: 2023-10-25]

name: EU LEGAL FRAMEWORK
description: The EU legal framework is a set of laws and policies that the EU Commissioner is relying on to protect Europeans' fundamental rights and address the risk of content-scanning mission creep [Source: TechCrunch, Time: 2023-10-25]

name: RULE OF LAW
description: The rule of law is a principle or policy that the EU Commissioner is invoking to address the risk of content-scanning mission creep and to justify the actions of the Commission [Source: TechCrunch, Time: 2023-10-25]
